<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
    <!--
        ╔══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
        ║  Apollo entitlements                                      ║
        ╚══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝

        Sandbox ON. This restricts what a compromised Apollo
        process can reach — important because the bundle ships
        adhoc-signed (no Developer ID yet), so a code-injection
        bug would otherwise inherit the user's full filesystem
        and Keychain. The entitlements below grant ONLY what
        Apollo needs to function:

          • network.client       — HTTPS to ClickUp, Google,
                                   GitHub Pages (Sparkle feed),
                                   OpenAI/Groq/Gemini.
          • network.server       — localhost listener for OAuth
                                   redirect (GoogleAuthService).
          • files.user-selected
                  .read-write     — NSOpenPanel attachment picker
                                    + drag-drop file URLs.
          • personal-information
                  .calendars      — EventKit reads, even though
                                    Google Calendar goes through
                                    REST. The system Calendar
                                    integration touches EventKit.
          • personal-information
                  .addressbook    — Contacts picker for invites.
          • automation
                  .apple-events   — AppleScript bridge that sends
                                    RSVPs to Calendar.app
                                    (described in
                                    NSAppleEventsUsageDescription).
        `com.apple.developer.usernotifications.time-sensitive`
        is intentionally OMITTED from this list. It's a
        restricted entitlement (requires a Developer ID team
        match) and AMFI silently fails the launch with code
        163 if an adhoc-signed app declares it. When you have a
        proper Developer ID cert and re-enable notarization in
        `release.sh`, add the key back here and rebuild.

        Sparkle: `SUEnableInstallerLauncherService` is flipped to
        true in Info.plist to match — Sparkle's installer can't
        replace the .app from inside the sandbox without its
        XPC service taking over the install step. Sparkle's
        framework ships with the needed `Installer.xpc` and
        `Downloader.xpc` already-bundled in our app.
    -->

    <key>com.apple.security.app-sandbox</key>
    <true/>

    <key>com.apple.security.network.client</key>
    <true/>

    <key>com.apple.security.network.server</key>
    <true/>

    <key>com.apple.security.files.user-selected.read-write</key>
    <true/>

    <key>com.apple.security.personal-information.calendars</key>
    <true/>

    <key>com.apple.security.personal-information.addressbook</key>
    <true/>

    <key>com.apple.security.automation.apple-events</key>
    <true/>
</dict>
</plist>
